1: Introduction¶

The concept of autism was coined in 1911 by the German psychiatrist Eugen Bleuler to describe a symptom of the most severe cases of schizophrenia. Today, professionals recognize that autism spectrum disorder, also known as ASD, encompasses a range of symptoms and severity levels, hence why autism is a “spectrum” disorder. Data science plays a growing role in understanding and supporting individuals with autism, especially in areas like diagnosis, intervention, and personalized care. Many data sets about autism are widely available. I have chosen to use the autism_prevalence_studies_20250325.csv dataset from the CDC. The CDC makes this information available at their website. In this project, I will investigate the 207 studies available in this data. According to the CDC, “this data table provides a collection of information from peer-reviewed autism prevalence studies. Information reported from each study includes the autism prevalence estimate and additional study characteristics (e.g., case ascertainment and criteria). Data were abstracted and included if the study fulfilled the following criteria: The study was published in English, produced at least one autism prevalence estimate; and was population-based (any age range) within a defined geographic area.” (CDC, Hanley)

In terms of positionality, I bring my own autism diagnosis as personal bias. Having had various diagnosis on the ASD from multiple professionals, I need to remain neutral and consider this as a form of research. In terms of sociotechnical systems, I must remember that the data spans a long range of time, during which the descriptors used to diagnose autism have changed with the evolving researching and DSMV. Earlier results may have been wrong and would have different diagnosis with current DSMV standards. Considering the results from the Power perspective, it’s important to remember these results come from a variety of countries and medical institutions. Individuals from different countries have a wide range of interpretation and personal experience and may insert their own bias into diagnosis, as they interpret the information found in the DSMV differently or may have different versions of the DSMV available. In terms of narrative, I am hopeful that the results of my project will help shape the discussion about autism being circulated in the news today. The idea that there has been a “spike” in autism diagnosis is not because there are more individuals with autism; rather, the information about diagnosis has evolved over the years. It is my hope that these results validate that idea.

In this project, I hope to answer various questions about these studies. Does a study’s sample size directly correlate to how many cases were reported? Autism diagnosis has increased over the years, due to the implementation of the DSMV. Will my research show this? Using the studies’ features, is it possible to predict where a study was conducted? Do all countries have the same statistics in terms of autistic diagnosis? And if not, why might that be? What are the minimum and cutoff ages for correctly diagnosing autism? This could be helpful for parents and medical professionals, as the earlier an individual is diagnosed with autism, the earlier treatment and therapies can begin. If there is a cutoff age, what might it be? Can adults be diagnosed with autism and receive treatment? Is there a way to predict when a study was/will be published? This might validate the idea that more individuals are diagnosed now rather than in the past, due to the DSMV. In conclusion, I am very curious to see the results, as ASD is a part of my everyday life.

This data table provides a collection of information from peer-reviewed autism prevalence studies. Information reported from each study includes the autism prevalence estimate and additional study characteristics (e.g., case ascertainment and criteria). A PubMed search was conducted to identify studies published at any time through September 2020 using the search terms: autism (title/abstract) OR autistic (title/abstract) AND prevalence (title/abstract). Data were abstracted and included if the study fulfilled the following criteria:

  • The study was published in English;
  • The study produced at least one autism prevalence estimate; and
  • The study was population-based (any age range) within a defined geographic area.

There are multiple issues with this dataset that will have to be addressed. The biggest issue by far is that some columns have nothing but null values, meaning that I will have to either not include them in my studies or add values to them. Another issue about this dataset is that some statitistics are classified as "objects" (strings) because they contain characters that are not digits (e.g. the alphabet, parenthesis, semicolons, etc.). This will be fixed by removing all of the non-numerical characters. Lastly, some cells have more than one value, which can be fixed by removing them or changing them to say "multiple methods/types".

autism = autism.fillna("0.0")

This line of code fills all of the NaN values with the string "0.0". This is because even though some statistics have numerical data, they are classified as "objects" (or strings) because as stated previously, they contain non-numerical characters.

These next several lines of code take on the role of One-hot data encoding since the values in the Case Identification Method, Case Criterion, and Autism Types Included all have cells with more than one variable, which causes the dataset to be "untidy".

In [5]:
mylist = []
for i in range(len(autism)): # Iterate over every item in the autism dataset
    index = 0
    for j in range(len(autism.at[i,"Case Identification Method"])): # Iterate through all of the items in the ith list from the "method" variable
        if " (" in autism.at[j, "Case Identification Method"]:
            index = autism.at[j, "Case Identification Method"].index(" (")
            mylist.append(autism.at[j, "Case Identification Method"][0:index])
        else:
            mylist.append(autism.at[j, "Case Identification Method"])
mylist = pd.Series(mylist).str.split('; ')
mylist2 = []
for i in range(len(mylist)):
    for j in range(len(mylist[i])):
        mylist2.append(mylist[i][j])
mylist2 = pd.unique(pd.Series(mylist2))

This block of code creates a list named mylist, which will contain all of the individual Case Identification Methods used in each study. Note that multiple cells in the Case Identification Method column have parenthesis, so the block of code accounts for this by splitting the elements in the Case Identification Method by the ( string if it is contained in the current "cell". After creating the list, it is then transformed into a pandas Series of strings split by semicolons because the original Case Identification Method column separates each method by semicolons.

Next, another list named mylist2 is created to contain all of the unique elements (case identification methods used) in the original mylist. It does so by iterating through all of the elements in mylist and adding each element to the second list. Lastly, mylist2 is turned into a pandas Series with only its (the list's) unique elements using the pd.unique() method.

mylist2 = pd.DataFrame(mylist2) # Convert mylist2 to a pandas DataFrame
# Iterate through all the items in the mylist DataFrame
for i in range(len(mylist2)):
    # Iterate through all of the items in the autism dataset
    for j in range(len(autism)):
        # Case 1: is the current item from the ith list in the jth cell of the "Case Identification Method" column?
        if mylist2[0][i] in autism.at[j, "Case Identification Method"]:
            autism.at[j,mylist2[0][i]]=True # Assigns True to the jth cell of the ith element of the 0th index of mylist
        # Case 2: is the current item from the ith list NOT in the jth cell of the "Case Identification Method" column?
        else:
            autism.at[j,mylist2[0][i]]=False # Assigns False to the jth cell of the ith element of the 0th index of mylist

This block of code transforms the unique Series of mylist2 into a DataFrame so that each of its elements can be iterated. The code also assigns the corresponding True or False value for each cell in the 7 newly created columns. It does so by iterating through all of the unique elements in mylist2, as well as checking to see if the current element in mylist2 is contained in the currently checked cell of the Case Identification Method column. If the Case Identification Method is used in a study, the code assigns True for the value of the current cell in its corresponding column. (E.G the code assigns "True" in row 44 of the "other method" column if "other methods" are contained in the 44th row of the Case Identification Method column, and assigns False otherwise.)

# Rename multiple columns in order to make things easier down the line.

This line of code renames multiple columns so that the coding will be easier to understand as well as making the column names cleaner. The columns that were renamed are as follows:

  1. ASD Prevalence Estimate per 1,000 was renamed to est_per_1000. This column indicates the estimate of the proportion of individuals diagnosed with autism per 1000 people.
  2. Male:Female Sex Ratio was renamed to sex_ratio. This column indicates the ratio of males with autism to females with autism.
  3. Non-Hispanic White:Hispanic Prevalence Ratio was renamed to hispanic_ratio. This column indicates the ratio of non-hispanic whites diagnosied with autism to hispanic individuals on the autism spectrum.
  4. White:Black Prevalence Ratio was renamed to skin_ratio because this column measures the ratio of individuals on the autism spectrum with white skin to individuals on with autism who have black skin.
  5. Diagnosis Mean Age (months) was renamed to mean_age_months. This column measures the average age (in months) of all of the people when they were diagnosed with autism.
  6. Diagnosis Median Age (months) was renamed to median_age_months. This column measures the median age (in months) of all of the individuals when they were diagnosed with autism.
  7. Non-Verbal or Minimally Verbal (%) was renamed to non_verbal_percentage. This column represents the percentage of autistic individuals in each study who were non-verbal or minimally verbal, meaning that they have not developed a language to speak.
  8. Percentage of Individual Co-occurring Conditions was renamed to condition_percentage. This column measures the percentage of autistic individuals who have multiple simultaneous mental disorders and/or health conditions.
  9. Adaptive Score <70 (%) was renamed to adaptive_score. This column measures the percentage of autistic individuals in each study who have an adaptive score lower than 70, meaning that they struggle in everyday skills such as communication and socialization
  10. IQ Score <70 (%) was renamed to iq_score. This column represents the percentage of individuals on the autism spectrum who scored less than 70 points on an IQ test.
  11. Sample Size was renamed to sample_size. This column represents the total number of participants in each individual study.
  12. Number of Cases was renamed to num_cases. This column represents the total number of individuals who were actually on the autism spectrum for each study.

3: Hypothesis Testing¶

Now that we know a bit more about the autism and the correlation of each studies' sample sizes and the amount of autistic individuals in each sample, we can now determine if this correlation is statistically significant. As stated before, there are some studies that have no specified sample size and/or number of autistic individuals reported a sample. This means that we need to exclude these studies, limiting our dataset.

In order to get a better understanding of the correlation between a study's sample size and the number of autistic individuals recorded in each sample, a scatter plot must be created with a "line of best fit". Note that a line of best fit (AKA a trend/regression line) is a straight line that best represents the relationship between a set of data points on a scatter plot. It helps visualize the correlation between 2 variables plotted on the scatter plot.

Recall that since both the sample_size and num_cases columns have a large range of values, it would be impossible to read a traditional scatter plot, meaning that both axes must use a logarithmic scale.

Since this scatter plot uses a logarithmic scale for both the x and y axes, it is difficult to create a line of best fit. However, by setting the method feature in the .transform_regression() method to "pow", it allows me to create a line of best fit for a scatter plot that uses logarithmic scales for both axes. Looking at this visualization. It appears that there is a strong positive correlation between a study's sample size and the number of autistic individuals present in each sample.

However, in order to prove that this correlation is strong, we will need to perform a hypothesis test of a correlation. Specifically, this hypothesis test will determine if the correlation between a study's sample size and the number of autistic individuals reported in a sample is statistically significant.

The first step to this hypothesis test is to state the null and alternative hypotheses, which are as follows:

  • Null hypothesis: There is no statistically significant correlation between a study's sample size and the number of autism cases reported in each sample.

  • Alternative hypothesis: There is a statistically significant correlation between a study's sample size and the number of autism cases reported in each sample. Specifically, this correlation is positive, meaning that as the sample size increases, so does the number of autism cases reported.

Since we are using a correlations hypothesis test, we need to create the following function:

In [60]:
def simulate_correlation(df,var1,var2):
    shuffled = df[var1].sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
    corr = shuffled.corr(df[var2])
    return corr

This block of code creates a function named simulate_correlation. This function takes in three arguments: The DataFrame itself (df) as well as two variables to correlate to each other (var1 and var2). The first line of code in this function assigns a random sample of the var1 column in the df DataFrame to a variable named shuffled. The line of code also makes sure to reset the indices of the df DataFrame, dropping the original indices to make sure that the DataFrame is properly shuffled. The second line of code in the simulate_correlation() function assigns the correlation coefficient of the shuffled DataFrame with var2 to a variable named corr. Lastly, the simulate_correlation() function returns the value of corr, which will be considered the value of one permutation of the df DataFrame.

In [61]:

In this case, the correlation coefficient is approximately 0.7, meaning that there is a relatively strong, positive correlation between each studies' sample size and the number of autistic individuals in each sample. However, this cannot be confirmed until several permuations of the autism_samples dataset have been performed.

4: Creating and Interpreting Models¶

4.1: Regression Models¶

4.1.1: Predicting the Minimum age when autism can be correctly diagnosed.¶

My first goal is to predict the minimum age at which autism can be correctly diagnosed. Because an age is a numerical value, I will need to run a regressor model. A regessor model is a statistical method used to examine and model the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. It aims to predict or explain how changes in the independent variable relate to changes in the dependent variable.

In this case, I am using a simple linear regression model to predict the minimum age at which autism can be diagnosed. A linear regression model aims to find the line that best fits the data points, allowing for predictions of the dependent/target variable based on the independent/predictor variable(s).

4.1.2: Predicting the potential cutoff age when autism can be correctly diagnosed.¶

My second goal is to predict the cutoff age at which autism can be correctly diagnosed (if one exists at all). As stated previously, an age is a numerical value, meaning I will need to run another regressor model.

In this case, I am using a K-Nearest-Neighbors (KNN for short) Regression Model. This type of model is distance-based, meaning it locates the "neighbors" with the shortest distances away from a specific data point.

An important thing to note about a KNN model is that the value of "k" needs to be chosen carefully, as a k value that is too low will cause the model to overfit the data, resulting in too much variance (choosing a training set too sensitive to changes). In contrast, a value of k that is too high will cause the model to underfit the data, resulting in too much bias (not accounting for the real-world scenarios, usually caused by bad assumptions in the learning algorithm). After trying several different values for k, I chose 7.

Another thing to note is that because KNN is a distance based model, predictor variables need to be standardized so that features with higher weights will not affect the model's performance.

This line of code creates a visualization the decision tree's results based on the predictor and target variables. The decision tree begins with ASD as the top of the tree, making it the most important variable for predicting when a study was published. If more than half of individuals found within the study are affected by ASD, then the decision tree assumes that they were most likely diagnosed using the DSM-IV, which stands for Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders Version 4, which is a version used by mental health professionals based on scientific literature to diagnose individuals with various mental disorders. This is denoted by a False result following arrows on the right. Continuing to the right, we can assume that these studies were published in 2012, as denoted the final false box on the right.

However, if less than half of these individuals are diagnosed using the DSM-IV version, then the decision tree checks for the number of recorded cases. If more than 987 autisic individuals were recorded in a study based on these 2 previous conditions, then we can assume that the study was conducted in 2019. Alternatively, if less than 987 autisitic individuals were recorded without using the DSM-IV, then the tree finally checks for the sex_ratio. In this case, if the ratio of autistic men to women is more than 3.15:1, then we can assume the study was conducted in 2012. Otherwise, the study was conducted in 2017.

Beginning again at the top of the decision tree with the ASD variable, if at most half of a study's individuals are affected by ASD, then the decision tree assumes that these individuals may have Kanners syndrome, which is a type of autism on the spectrum, denoted by the true arrow to the left. If more than half of these individuals are affected by Kanner, the decision tree assumes that the study was conducted in 1975. However, the squared_error is at its highest (50.688), meaning that the model's predictions are significantly different from the actual values, suggesting poor model performance or potential issues with the data/model itself. In other words, the model is not accurately capturing the relationships in the data and may be making large errors in its predictions.

If at most half of these individuals are affected by Kanner's syndrome, the tree checks to see if they are also affected by PDD-NOS, which means pervasive developmental disorder, Not otherwise specified. These individuals have some autistic-like behaviors, but are not considered (classically) autistic. (Note: I was diagnosed with this when I was 4 years old.). If more than half of these individuals are affected by PDD-NOS, then the model assumes that these studies were conducted in 2010. However, if at most half of these individuals are affected by PDD-NOS, then the tree checks the number of cases recorded in each study. If more than 517 cases are recorded, the model assumes that a study was conducted in 2009. Otherwise, the model checks for the sex_ratio of a study.

Continuing with sex_ratio as the predictor, if it is more than 1.45, the model checks to see if these select individuals were diagnosed with the ICD-10 code for ASD. This means the individual has pervasive developmental disorders, which is a specific code for ASD. If more than half of these individuals were diagnosed with this code, the model assumes that these studies were conducted in the year 2000. However, if at most half of these individuals were diagnosed with the ICD-10 code, the model checks to see if they were diagnosed using the DSM, which is an earlier version of DSM-IV. If more than half of these individuals were diagnosed using the DSM, then the model assumes that these studies were published in 1991. Otherwise, the model predicts these studies to be conducted in 1984.

Going back to sex_ratio, if it is less than 1.45, then the tree checks to see if the diagnosis method was clinical interpretation, which means that a medical professional used their best judgement of autistic-like behaviors to diagnose those on the spectrum. If more than half of these cases were diagnosed using a clinical interpretation, then the tree assumes that the study was published in 1997. Otherwise, the model predicts that the study was conducted in 2008.

Overall, results found on the left of the decision tree, denoted by the "True" arrows are not to be trusted because they have very high squared_errors, ranging from 15 to a massive 256. Results on the right of the decision tree, as denoted by the first "False" arrow are more trustworthy because they have lower squared_error values, ranging from 5 to 21.

In order to validate my model, I will need to perform a classification_report to obtain my accuracy scores. Looking at the report, only 35% of studies were correctly classified. The precision scores for England, Sweden, and the USA were 0.11, 0.50, and 0.59, respectively. This means that the model correctly predicted 11% of studies in the test data to be from England, 50% of studies in the test data to be from Sweden, and 59% of studies to be conducted in the USA.

The recall scores for England, Sweden, and the USA were 0.40, 0.29, and 0.36, respectively. This means that 40% of all studies that were conducted in England were correctly classified, 29% of studies that were conducted in Sweden were correctly classified, and 36% of studies conducted in the USA were correctly classified.

Note: Since this is not a binary classification model, there is no specificity (which is the recall score of the other category).

Based on these results, I can conclude that the model performed poorly due to the low accuracy, precision, and recall scores.

Overall, there is a positive correlation between a study’s sample size and the number of autistic individuals diagnosed in each sample. These results can be trusted because the p-value for my hypothesis test was exactly 0.0, and the correlation coefficient between sample_size and num_cases was around 0.7. However, there is not enough data to answer my other questions. This is because all of my other models had mediocre results at best, and at worst could not predict when a study was published. This could be corrected by choosing a dataset with more data about autism prevalence.

Despite my models’ poor results, many studies find that individuals are usually diagnosed by the age of 2 and there is no specific “cutoff” age when autism cannot be diagnosed.
